## Methodology
methods.
Advances in functional neuroimaging methods, such as
functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), positron
emission tomography (PET), and single-photon emission
computed tomography (SPECT), have enabled the explora-
tion of dynamic neural changes involved in the pathophysiol-
ogy of PTSD. In PET and SPECT, a radioactive tracer is ad-
ministered to quantify regional brain metabolism or regional
cerebral blood flow, providing a measure of neuronal activity.
In contrast, fMRI is based on the intrinsic blood-oxygen-level
dependent (BOLD) signal and does not require the adminis-
tration of a tracer. By measuring regional metabolic or blood
flow changes, PET and SPECT inherently provide a more
direct estimates of neuronal activation; while in fMRI, several
techniques have been developed to indirectly quantify this
activity. For example, the amplitudes of low-frequency fluc-
tuations (ALFFs) of the BOLD signal can be quantified as a
