the CEN, and the DMN may underlie the psychopathology of PTSD.
According to this model, the SN is hyperconnected and hyperactive and
has a low threshold for perceived saliency (underlying symptoms of
hyperarousal) and is incapable of efficient DMN-CEN modulation (i.e.,
switching between task-relevant and task-irrelevant behavior); the CEN is a
weakly interconnected and hypoactive (paralleling impaired cognition) and is
incapable of top-down SN regulation; finally, the DMN is a weakly
interconnected and hypoactive resulting in disrupted ability to maintain a
calm inner state (intrusive symptoms), altered sense of self/world
